# Financial Accounting
- Provides financial information on a business's recent financial performance, targeted at external users (shareholders, employees)
- Backward looking
- Works according to accounting standards and government regulations
- Focused on the [[Income statement]], [[Balance sheet]] and [[Cash flow statement]]


# Management Accounting
- Serves primarily the internal needs of the organisation
- Provides financial and non-financial information to managers for costing, planning, control and performance, and for decision making 
- Not required by law (like financial accounting)
- Lots of tools and techniques

## Strategic Planning 
From an accounting perspective, strategic planning involves BSC, and budgeting (which are interrelated): 
- Strtagey and budgeting go hand to hand - budgeting can be instrumental in implementing strategy 
- In order to create a strategy you need to look at where you are now and where you want to be - strategic budgets will reflect the implementation of the strategy
- [[Balanced scorecard|Balanced scorecard]]
- [[Budgeting|Budgeting]]

## Decision Making
- Costs and cost volume profit
- Limiting facotrs and theory of constriants
- Captial investment appriasal and NPV (long term deciisions)
- Different management accounting tools can support short term and long term decisions
	- Defining short vs long term decisions: short term decisions are those where you will see an immeidate impact (in the next 2 years) eg ceasing production,  build or buy, maximising limited factors (labour or machine capacity)
	- Differnece between LT and ST is about the implications of the decisions
	- Long term decisions involve choices around long term capacity of an organisation, typically capital investment appraisal (eg setting up a new factory)- typically longer than 2 years
	- We're talking about fixed costs (costs that are difficult to reverse) with LT 
		- 5 techniques for Captial Investment Appriasal
			- Payback period
			- Accounting rate of return
			- NPV - number 1 method
				- Calculate initial cash flows
				- Choose disciunt rate (often company's cost of capital)
				- Discount original cash flows
				- Match discounted cash flows against initial investment 
				- Positive NPV is good - higher the better 
			- Profitability index
			- Internal rate of return (IRR) - close second
- Costs and revenues are typically influenced by short-term and long-term decisions
	- Different types of costs: direct and indirect, fixed and variable
		- Fixed cost - don not change with volume
		- Variable cost - do change with volume
		- In the short term, only variable costs are relevatn because you can't change fixed costs in the short term
	**- [[Cost volume profit model|Cost volume profit model]]
	- Contribution margins (difference between price and short term variable cost) is often crucial in short term decisions. An example is break even analysis,
